"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747438","Home Office","false","2017-07-17","<p>Tackling knife crime is a priority for the Government. Our Modern Crime Prevention Strategy published in March 2016 set out a range of measures to strengthen our response to knife crime. Our work to tackle knife crime is centred on four key strands – working with the police on operations and enforcement, work on legislative framework, work with retailers on responsible sales, and early intervention and prevention.</p><p> </p><p>We are taking firm action including encouraging police forces to undertake a series of coordinated national weeks of action to tackle knife crime under Operation Sceptre. The operation includes targeting habitual knife carriers, weapon sweeps, test purchases of knives from identified retailers, and the use of surrender bins. The Home Office hosted a national briefing event for police forces on Operation Sceptre on 14 June and a record twenty nine police forces are expected to be involved in the next week of action planned for mid July.</p><p> </p><p>Local authorities are responsible for assessing need for youth services and allocating funding. The Government is supporting local authorities and the youth sector by investing to help youth organisations demonstrate their impact. The Government is investing in the National Citizen Service, investing up to £80 million through the ‘# iwill’ social action campaign and ‘Youth Investment Funds’ to help young people develop skills, improve their wellbeing and contribute to their communities. The Government is also investing in the ‘Delivering Differently for Young People’ programme, which helped local authorities develop new models for delivering on their statutory duty to provide positive activities for young people.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-07-17T15:51:33.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747438/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747438/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747438/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-03",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what priority they attach to reducing the increasing levels of knife crime; and when they intend to restore spending levels for youth services to assist local initiatives in this area.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747439","Department for Education","false","2017-07-24","<p>We are already working to deliver the commitments on equalities made in the Queen’s Speech, including bringing forward legislation to protect the victims of domestic violence and abuse, making further progress to tackle pay gaps, reforming mental health legislation and strengthening enforcement of the Equality Act 2010.</p><p> </p><p>We will announce our detailed plans and intended timetables in due course<em>. </em></p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-07-24T14:33:11.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747439/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747439/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747439/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-03",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government how, and when, they intend to honour the pledge in the Queen's Speech "to make progress to tackle discrimination against people on the basis of their race, faith, gender, disability or sexual orientation".","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747440","Home Office","false","2017-07-12","<p>The Government maintains a Shortage Occupation List, based on expert advice from the independent Migration Advisory Committee. The list comprises skilled jobs, including public sector roles, where there is an identified national shortage. Jobs on the list are given priority when allocating places within the Tier 2 immigration limit.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-07-12T11:47:05.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747440/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747440/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747440/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-03",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government whether, in the light of staff shortages in the key areas of teaching and the NHS, they intend to remove public service jobs from the immigration cap.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL404"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747441","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-13","<p>The Cutting Red Tape programme was a series of reviews of regulation and its implementation run jointly by the Cabinet Office and BEIS during the 2015-17 Parliament. Building regulations were relevant to the Cutting Red Tape Review into House Building which was published in February 2017 and focused specifically on new builds. The report did not make recommendations, but reported the findings from consultation with business and other interests, including areas where there might be overlap and duplication between planning conditions and building regulations. The findings of the review helped to inform the Housing White Paper which was published at the same time.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-07-13T10:58:46.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747441/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747441/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747441/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-03",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government whether they are planning to assess the impact of the Cabinet Office Cutting Red Tape programme on building safety; if so, what those plans are; and if not, whether they will consider doing so.","false","Biography information for Lord Rennard",,"Lord Rennard","HL405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747442","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-13","<p>The Government has not yet decided how its better regulation system, including any One-In, Two-Out policy, will operate in this Parliament.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-07-13T17:01:25.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747442/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747442/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747442/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-03",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government, in the light of the Grenfell Tower disaster, what plans they have to review their one-in, two-out policy for new regulations.","false","Biography information for Lord Rennard",,"Lord Rennard","HL406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747443","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-13","<p>The Government has not yet published a final record of its total regulatory impact on business for the 2015-17 Parliament. Therefore it is not yet possible to calculate the savings from the introduction of the 5p charge on plastic bags as a proportion of the total reduction in regulatory costs on business.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-07-13T10:46:21.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747443/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747443/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747443/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-03",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what is their estimate of the proportion of the total reduction in regulatory costs on business since 2015 that has resulted from the introduction of the 5p charge on plastic bags.","false","Biography information for Lord Rennard",,"Lord Rennard","HL407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747444","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-13","<p>In June 2016 the Government reported net savings to business of £885 million from regulatory provisions that counted towards its Business Impact Target during the first year of the 2015-17 Parliament. The Government has not yet published a final report covering the whole of the 2015-17 Parliament.</p><p>The Government does not have an estimate of the expected regulatory impact on business for the period between now and 2020.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-07-13T10:58:10.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747444/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747444/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747444/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-03",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what is their estimate of the total reduction in regulatory costs on business since 2015; and what is their estimate of the total reduction expected by 2020.","false","Biography information for Lord Rennard",,"Lord Rennard","HL408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747445","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-13","<p>Deregulatory budgets were agreed between Ministers for a number of departments with regulatory responsibility during the 2015-17 Parliament. The Government has not yet decided what approach it will take to deliver better regulation during the current Parliament.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-07-13T10:46:46.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747445/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747445/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747445/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-03",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what are the individual budgets agreed between the Better Regulation Executive and Government departments with regulatory responsibility; and what progress has been made against those targets to date.","false","Biography information for Lord Rennard",,"Lord Rennard","HL409"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747446","Home Office","false","2017-07-14","<p>The Home Office is committed to publishing data in an orderly way as part of the regular quarterly Immigration Statistics, in line with the Code of Practice for Official Statistics. The Government has committed to resettling to the UK up to 3,000 individuals under the Vulnerable Children’s Resettlement Scheme (VCRS). Data on the number of people who have been resettled under this scheme will be published in future releases of the Home Office’s immigration quarterly statistics. Latest statistics published on 25 May confirmed that a total of 360 Iraqis have been resettled to the UK under the Gateway scheme, and 18 under the Mandate scheme, during the period 1 January 2014 until 31 March 2017.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-07-14T12:14:59.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747446/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747446/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747446/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-03",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government how many Iraqi refugees they have resettled since 2014 under (1) the Vulnerable Children's Resettlement Scheme (VCRS), and (2) other global resettlement schemes such as Gateway and Mandate.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Southwark",,"The Lord Bishop of Southwark","HL410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747447","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-11","<p>The UK is working closely with the UN to monitor the humanitarian situation in Gaza. We are also funding basic service delivery in Gaza through the UN Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees. We urge all the parties to find a sustainable solution to the current energy situation.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-07-11T16:43:23.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747447/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747447/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747447/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-07-03",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking to respond to the deteriorating humanitarian situation in Gaza, following the decision by the government of Israel to implement a request from the Palestinian Authority to reduce the flow of electricity supplies from Israel to Gaza.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Southwark",,"The Lord Bishop of Southwark","HL411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747448","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-17","<p>The Government has been clear that we want to have reached an agreement about our future partnership by the time the two year Article 50 process has ended, in March 2019.</p><p>Within that time, we will work to secure a deal that works for Britain and for Europe. We are delivering on the result of the referendum and the UK will leave the EU in 2019. While we do not propose to give a running commentary on the negotiations, providing certainty to businesses and individuals is our priority, and we will do so as early as possible where we can.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-07-17T15:54:28.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747448/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747448/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747448/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-03",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government whether they will reject any proposals to extend the negotiating period to leave the European Union beyond two years and whether they will use their best endeavours to conclude negotiations sooner than the two year period laid down in Article 50 of the Lisbon Treaty.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747449","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-11","<p>The Christmas Bonus was introduced in 1972 and was £10. If it had been increased in line with the cost of living, in 2016 its current value would be approximately £133. If it had been increased in line with average earnings, in 2016 it would be approximately £202.</p>",,"Baroness Buscombe",,"2017-07-11T15:24:33.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747449/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747449/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747449/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-03",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government, further to the answer by Lord Henley on 1 March concerning the Pensioners' Christmas Bonus (HL5502) what would the value of the £10 bonus be in real terms had the bonus been increased in line with the cost of living and increases in incomes.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747450","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-13","<p>The Government believes in a strong United Kingdom Parliament for a strong United Kingdom. English votes for English laws embeds fairness and balance into Parliament’s law making process, strengthening England’s voice, just as devolution has strengthened the voices of Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland within our Union. We therefore do not believe there is public appetite or need for an English Parliament. English Votes for English Laws ensures English matters are approved by English MPs.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-07-13T12:04:36.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747450/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747450/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747450/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-03",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government, further to the answer by Lord Young of Cookham concerning an English Parliament (HL4548) whether they will explain why an English Parliament would detract from a strong United Kingdom whilst a Scottish Parliament does not.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747451","Department for Education","false","2017-07-12","<p>Schools and local authorities have had the power to issue penalty notices since 2004.</p><p>Every local authority must draw up a Code of Conduct for issuing penalty notices, in consultation with governing bodies and head teachers in their area. The Code will set out the occasions when it will be appropriate to issue a penalty notice. This can for example include circumstances where a pupil is persistently late to school without a valid reason. A penalty notice must be issued in accordance with that Code.</p><p>There is no formal appeals process where a parent is issued with a penalty notice and they deem this to be incorrect; however, parents can discuss their situation with the local authority and ask for the penalty notice to be withdrawn. If the penalty notice has not been paid in full by end of the 28 day period allowed for payment and if the local authority has not commenced prosecution of the parent and is not contemplating doing so, it must withdraw the penalty notice.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-07-12T11:46:30.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747451/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747451/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747451/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-03",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government whether schools or local authorities have the legal power to fine parents of children who are late for school and if so, whether there is the right of appeal through the courts.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747452","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-12","<p>The Government launched its five year National Cyber Security Strategy in 2016 to ensure that the UK has the right capability and capacity to defend our people, businesses, and assets; deter our adversaries; and develop the skills and capabilities we need across the public and private sectors.</p><p>A significant early milestone to support delivery of the Strategy was the formation of the National Cyber Security Centre. Implementation of the Strategy including the role and powers of the National Cyber Security Centre are subject to continual review to ensure that we are responding at the scale and pace required to meet the challenges we face.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-07-12T16:12:07.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747452/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747452/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747452/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-03",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government whether they have any plans to review (1) the National Cyber Security Strategy, and (2) the role and powers of the National Cyber Security Centre.","false","Biography information for Lord Truscott",,"Lord Truscott","HL416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747454","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-26","<p>The Government has received the report of Public Administration and Constitutional Affairs Committee on the Iraq Inquiry, and will be responding in due course, setting out the lessons learned.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-07-26T10:11:18.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747454/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747454/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747454/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-03","Iraq Committee of Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when he expects the lessons learned investigation across Whitehall co-ordinated by the National Security Adviser to report.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","2445"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747455","Home Office","false","2017-07-06","<p>A third generation of synthetic cannabinoids was controlled under class B of the Misuse of Drugs Act 1971 in December. Synthetic cannabinoids are commonly found under a number of brand names, including ‘spice’ and ‘black mamba’, which contain a wide range of these substances that varies from sample to sample.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-07-06T15:34:49.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747455/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747455/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747455/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-03","Synthetic Cannabinoids: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the Government's policy is on the legal status of (a) Spice, (b) Black Mamba and (c) the new highly potent and lethal crystalised form of Spice.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","2406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747456","Home Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>The Government expects police and forensic service providers to follow locally agreed processes for conducting forensic analysis for samples of synthetic cannabinoids or any other substances in order to prosecute under the Misuse of Drugs Act 1971.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-07-10T16:16:00.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747456/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747456/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747456/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-03","Synthetic Cannabinoids: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what measures are in place in (a) Greater Manchester and (b) the rest of the UK to test for the presence of the new crystalised form of the drug Spice.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","2370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747457","Home Office","false","2017-07-13","<p>Jewish places of worship are unable to apply under the places of worship security scheme as a separate commitment was already in place to fund Jewish community sites via a grant administered through the Community Security Trust (CST).</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-07-13T15:55:21.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747457/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747457/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747457/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-03","Places of Worship Security Funding Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many Jewish places of worship from each denomination had applied for funding under the Places of Worship Security Funding Scheme by 1 June 2017 in each region.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","2481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747458","Home Office","false","2017-07-11","<p>Contingency planning for multiple fire incidents is the responsibility of each local fire and rescue authority. Each fire and rescue authority has a statutory requirement to have mutual assistance arrangements in place to provide additional support including during major fires and other emergencies, and to review and test their arrangements. Local mutual assistance arrangements are augmented by national resilience capabilities available from across the country.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","2476","2017-07-11T12:38:35.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747458/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747458/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747458/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-03","Fires: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what information her Department holds on contingency planning for multiple fire incidents across London.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","2475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747459","Home Office","false","2017-07-11","<p>Contingency planning for multiple fire incidents is the responsibility of each local fire and rescue authority. Each fire and rescue authority has a statutory requirement to have mutual assistance arrangements in place to provide additional support including during major fires and other emergencies, and to review and test their arrangements. Local mutual assistance arrangements are augmented by national resilience capabilities available from across the country.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","2475","2017-07-11T12:38:35.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747459/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747459/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747459/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-03","Fires: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what information her Department holds on contingency planning for multiple fire incidents across Greater Manchester.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","2476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747460","Home Office","false","2017-07-11","<p>The Home Office keeps the UK’s preparedness for terrorist attack under constant review, and is delivering a £144 million programme to increase numbers of armed police officers in the UK. The Home Office also trains and equips specialist fire and ambulance teams to manage casualties in higher risk environments. These capabilities are deployable to a terrorist incident occurring anywhere in the UK, including London.</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office’s National CT Exercise programme plays a vital role in ensuring that Government, blue light responders, military and other agencies are prepared to respond to terrorist attacks in the UK. The programme comprises large-scale live exercises that test the national response to a terrorist attack, and also includes regional and table-top exercises.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-07-11T12:33:16.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747460/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747460/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747460/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-03","Terrorism: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what information her Department holds on contingency planning for multiple terrorist incidents across London.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","2477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747461","Home Office","false","2017-07-11","<p>The Home Office keeps the UK’s preparedness for terrorist attack under constant review, and is delivering a £144 million programme to increase numbers of armed police officers in the UK. The Home Office also trains and equips specialist fire and ambulance teams to manage casualties in higher risk environments. These capabilities are deployable to a terrorist incident occurring anywhere in the UK, including in Greater Manchester.</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office’s National CT Exercise Programme plays a vital role in ensuring that Government, blue light responders, military and other agencies are prepared to respond to terrorist attacks throughout the UK. Exercise WINCHESTER ACCORD was delivered in Greater Manchester in May 2016. The exercise tested the emergency service and military response to a suicide bomb and firearms attack on a crowded place.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-07-11T12:34:15.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747461/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747461/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/747461/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-03","Terrorism: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what information her Department holds on contingency planning for multiple terrorist incidents across Greater Manchester.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","2478"
